Install `jazz-napi` directly and create one server-only context for the process:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH! },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});
```

Use a stable, writable `dataPath`; a memory driver is ephemeral and must have an upstream `serverUrl`. Reuse this context across requests—do not initialize a native runtime per request—and call `await jazz.shutdown()` during process termination. Await the required write tier before returning success when durability is part of the endpoint contract. Keep `BACKEND_SECRET` and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` server-only and out of public-prefixed environment variables; server-connected backend/request-scoped handles require `backendSecret`.

Upload with edge settlement and only report success after both file creation and parent insertion settle:
```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });
const upload = await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label,
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```
Download with an edge read so missing local chunks can be fetched:
```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  // consume blob
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof FileNotFoundError) showMissingFile();
  else if (error instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) showIncompleteFile(error.reason);
  else throw error;
}
```
Treat `missing-part`, `part-size-mismatch`, and `invalid-file-record` as incomplete/corrupt data; a stronger tier can fetch absent local data but cannot repair bad upstream data.

Keep the parent relationship alive until inherited deletes finish: load the upload, load its file metadata, delete every referenced part, delete the file row, and delete the upload last.
```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    await db.delete(app.file_parts, partId).wait({ tier: "edge" });
  }
  await db.delete(app.files, file.id).wait({ tier: "edge" });
}
await db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```
Deleting the upload first removes the relationship used by inherited file and part delete policies, potentially leaving orphaned chunks.

Render from a subscription with `localUpdates: "immediate"` and `propagation: "full"` so edits appear immediately. For every mutation, retain its write handle and track a UI state such as `pending → confirmed | rejected`:

```ts
const write = db.update(app.documents, id, patch);
setStatus("pending");
void write.wait({ tier: "edge" }).then(
  () => setStatus("confirmed"),
  error => setStatus({ kind: "rejected", error })
);
```

An edge wait remains pending while disconnected. Show an offline/pending indicator, call `db.reconnect()` on the owning unscoped database, and keep waiting rather than reporting success prematurely. If authority rejects the mutation, explain that the optimistic value may roll back and offer retry or conflict recovery. Also register and dispose `db.onMutationError(...)` for un-awaited or restart-surviving failures.

Use two real in-memory clients against `startLocalJazzServer`, write through Alice, await edge durability, then poll Bob. Since order is not under test, normalize by a stable key:

```ts
const rows = [
  { id: "a", title: "Alpha" },
  { id: "b", title: "Beta" },
  { id: "c", title: "Gamma" },
];

for (const row of rows) {
  await alice.insert(app.todos, row).wait({ tier: "edge" });
}

await vi.waitFor(async () => {
  const synced = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
  expect(synced.map(({ id, title }) => ({ id, title })).sort((a, b) =>
    a.id.localeCompare(b.id)
  )).toEqual(rows);
});
```

Alternatively, add an explicit `orderBy` to the query. Shut down both clients and stop the server in teardown; do not use fixed sleeps.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` with Alice and Bob sessions. Create the row as Alice, assert Bob's read is filtered out, and independently assert update/delete rejection:

```ts
const alice = testApp.as({
  user_id: "alice",
  claims: {},
  authMode: "local-first",
});
const bob = testApp.as({
  user_id: "bob",
  claims: {},
  authMode: "local-first",
});

const row = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Private" }).value;

await expect(
  bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: row.id }))
).resolves.toEqual([]);

bob.expectDenied((db) =>
  db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Unauthorized" })
);
bob.expectDenied((db) => db.delete(app.todos, row.id));

alice.expectAllowed((db) =>
  db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Owner update" })
);
```

Denied reads return no rows rather than throwing. Initialize the policy app in `beforeEach` and call `testApp.shutdown()` in `afterEach`.
